{"title_page": "John A. Macdonald Memorial (Grandmaison)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Macdonald Monument}}\n{{short description|Sculpture of John A. Macdonald by Sonia de Grandmaison and John Cullen Nugent}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Sculpture\n | image_file = Macdonaldstat.jpg\n | image_size = 225px\n | title  = John A. Macdonald Memorial\n | subject = [[John A. Macdonald ]]\n | artist = Sonia de Grandmaison <br /> [[John Cullen Nugent]]\n | year   = 1967\n | medium   = [[Bronze sculpture|Bronze]]\n | height_metric = 1.874\n | height_imperial = \n | width_metric    = 1.905\n | width_imperial  = \n | length_metric   = 0.518\n | length_imperial = \n | metric_unit = m\n | imperial_unit = ft\n | city   = [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]], [[Saskatchewan]], [[Canada]]\n}}\n\nThe '''John A. Macdonald Memorial''' is a [[public sculpture]] in [[bronze]] of [[Sir John A. Macdonald]] by Sonia de Grandmaison and [[John Cullen Nugent]], located at the south entrance to [[Victoria Park, Regina|Victoria Park]], [[Regina, Saskatchewan]], Canada. It is the last statue of Macondald still standing in a public space in a major Western Canadian city.\n\n==Work==\nSituated at the south entrance to [[Victoria Park, Regina|Victoria Park]], the [[bronze sculpture]] was cast in five pieces by using a \"lost wax technique\", and soldered together by artist [[John Cullen Nugent]],<ref name=\"Grandmaison\">{{cite book |title=Downtown Regina Public Art Guide |date=2014 |publisher=Regina Downtown Business Improvement District |location=Regina |page=14 |url=https://reginadowntown.ca/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/PublicArtGuide2014-101514web.pdf |accessdate=2 April 2020 |chapter=Sonia de Grandmaison: Sir John A. MacDonald (1966-67)}}</ref> a technique he learned from candlemaking. It stands 1.874 \u00d7 1.905 \u00d7 0.518 m.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Krueger |first1=Jan |title=Prairie Pots and Beyond. Volume 2 |date=2006 |publisher=[[Carleton University]] |page=61 |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/ea0c/7df4f715a5ba6e7201692aa525905eb9d7a8.pdf |accessdate=2 April 2020 |format=thesis (M.A.)}}</ref>\n\nThe plaque underneath the statue reads \"John A. Macdonald, Father of Confederation.\"\n\n==History==\nFundraising in Regina for a statue to commemorate Macdonald's achievements as [[Canada]]'s first [[Prime Minister]] began in 1891 after Macdonald's death, but it was not commissioned until 1966.<ref name=\"Grandmaison\" /> The statue was officially unveiled in 1967, the year of the [[Canadian Centennial]].\n\nReassessments of Macondald's role in Canadian history, particularly his [[Cultural assimilation of Native Americans|assimilation]]ist policies toward [[Indigenous Canadians]] and [[racist]] views of Asian immigrants,<ref name=\"Fougere\">{{cite news |last1=White-Crummey |first1=Arthur |title=Regina mayor has no desire to follow Victoria's lead on Sir John A. Macdonald statue |url=https://leaderpost.com/news/local-news/regina-mayor-has-no-desire-to-follow-victorias-lead-on-john-a-macdonald-statue/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[Regina Leader-Post]] |date=10 August 2018}}</ref> led to statues of Macdonald being vandalized and removed in other cities in the first decades of the 21st century. The Regina memorial was vandalized at least three times between 2012 and 2018.<ref name=\"Postey\">{{cite news |last1=Postey |first1=Drew |title=Despite recent controversy Mayor Fougere disappointed to see MacDonald statue vandalized |url=https://www.620ckrm.com/2018/08/22/despite-recent-controversy-mayor-fougere-dissapinted-to-see/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=620 CKRM |date=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Call for removal===\nIn August 2017, a [[petition]] was launched for the removal of the Regina memorial.<ref name=\"Petition\">{{cite news |title=Petition calls for removal of John A. Macdonald statue in Regina |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/petition-remove-john-a-macdonald-statue-regina-1.4266149 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[CBC News]] |agency=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=29 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the removal of a statue in [[Victoria, British Columbia]] in 2018, the Regina memorial was the only Macdonald statue still standing in a major city in [[Western Canada]], one of a \"handful\" across the country.<ref name=\"Latimer\">{{cite news |last1=Latimer |first1=Kendall |title=Last John A. Macdonald statue in major Western Canada city seen painted 'red handed' |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/john-a-macdonald-statue-regina-vandalism-1.4795082 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=CBC News |date=23 August 2018}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|name=first|Statues elsewhere in Canada include the [[Macdonald Monument]] in Montreal and smaller works in [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]], [[Baden, Ontario|Baden]], and Macondald's home town [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]].<ref name=\"Yun\">{{cite journal |last1=Yun |first1=Tom |title=Where Sir John A. Macdonald stands in Canada: an interactive map |journal=[[Maclean's]] |date=19 August 2018 |url=https://www.macleans.ca/news/canada/where-sir-john-a-macdonald-stands-in-canada-an-interactive-map/ |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>}} That year, it was vandalized with spray paint in February<ref>{{cite news |title=John A. MacDonald statue in Victoria Park vandalized |url=https://www.cruzfm.com/syn/343/161331/john-a-macdonald-statue-in-victoria-park-vandalized/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=Cruz FM |date=23 February 2018}}</ref> and again on 21 August.<ref name=\"Latimer\" /> [[Vibank]] musician Patrick Johnson contacted the ''[[Regina Leader-Post]]'' to claim responsibility, saying it was an act of \"peaceful protest\", and that he painted the statue's hands red \"to symbolize the blood... on Macdonald's hands.\"<ref name=\"Johnson\">{{cite web |title=John A. Macdonald statue vandal says he painted Regina monument as a 'peaceful protest' |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/john-a-macdonald-vandal-patrick-johnson-1.4801743 |website=CBC News |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> He claimed to have painted the statue once before, after the verdict in [[Gerald Stanley]]'s trial.<ref name=\"Johnson\" />\n\n===Opposition to removal===\nRegina's mayor Michael Fougere characterized calls for the statue to remove the statue as trying \"to erase history\", but said he would be  receptive to the idea of a plaque that would \"contextualize\" Macdonald, since \"many things that he did are certainly difficult to accept by today's standards \u2014 and we should know about that.\"<ref name=\"Fougere\" /> After the statue was vandalized for the third time August 2018, he reiterated his earlier statements, and added \"it's important to remember MacDonald's contributions to Indigenous and women's voting rights.\"<ref name=\"Postey\" />\n\n==Note==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord |50.447547|N|104.612346|W|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sir John A. Macdonald Statue}}\n[[Category:1967 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Regina, Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:John A. Macdonald]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Saskatchewan]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Macdonald Monument}}\n{{short description|Sculpture of John A. Macdonald by Sonia de Grandmaison and John Cullen Nugent}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Sculpture\n | image_file = Macdonaldstat.jpg\n | image_size = 225px\n | title  = John A. Macdonald Memorial\n | subject = [[John A. Macdonald ]]\n | artist = Sonia de Grandmaison <br /> [[John Cullen Nugent]]\n | year   = 1967\n | medium   = [[Bronze sculpture|Bronze]]\n | height_metric = 1.874\n | height_imperial = \n | width_metric    = 1.905\n | width_imperial  = \n | length_metric   = 0.518\n | length_imperial = \n | metric_unit = m\n | imperial_unit = ft\n | city   = [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]], [[Saskatchewan]], [[Canada]]\n}}\n\nThe '''John A. Macdonald Memorial''' is a [[public sculpture]] in [[bronze]] of [[Sir John A. Macdonald]] by Sonia de Grandmaison and [[John Cullen Nugent]], located at the south entrance to [[Victoria Park, Regina|Victoria Park]], [[Regina, Saskatchewan]], Canada. It is the last statue of Macondald still standing in a public space in a major Western Canadian city.\n\n==Work==\nSituated at the south entrance to [[Victoria Park, Regina|Victoria Park]], the [[bronze sculpture]] was cast in five pieces by using a \"lost wax technique\", and soldered together by artist [[John Cullen Nugent]],<ref name=\"Grandmaison\">{{cite book |title=Downtown Regina Public Art Guide |date=2014 |publisher=Regina Downtown Business Improvement District |location=Regina |page=14 |url=https://reginadowntown.ca/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/PublicArtGuide2014-101514web.pdf |accessdate=2 April 2020 |chapter=Sonia de Grandmaison: Sir John A. MacDonald (1966-67)}}</ref> a technique he learned from candlemaking. It stands 1.874 \u00d7 1.905 \u00d7 0.518 m.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Krueger |first1=Jan |title=Prairie Pots and Beyond. Volume 2 |date=2006 |publisher=[[Carleton University]] |page=61 |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/ea0c/7df4f715a5ba6e7201692aa525905eb9d7a8.pdf |accessdate=2 April 2020 |format=thesis (M.A.)}}</ref>\n\nThe plaque underneath the statue reads \"John A. Macdonald, Father of Confederation.\"\n\n==History==\nFundraising in Regina for a statue to commemorate Macdonald's achievements as [[Canada]]'s first [[Prime Minister]] began in 1891 after Macdonald's death, but it was not commissioned until 1966.<ref name=\"Grandmaison\" /> The statue was officially unveiled in 1967, the year of the [[Canadian Centennial]].\n\nReassessments of Macondald's role in Canadian history, particularly his [[Cultural assimilation of Native Americans|assimilation]]ist policies toward [[Indigenous Canadians]] and [[racist]] views of Asian immigrants,<ref name=\"Fougere\">{{cite news |last1=White-Crummey |first1=Arthur |title=Regina mayor has no desire to follow Victoria's lead on Sir John A. Macdonald statue |url=https://leaderpost.com/news/local-news/regina-mayor-has-no-desire-to-follow-victorias-lead-on-john-a-macdonald-statue/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[Regina Leader-Post]] |date=10 August 2018}}</ref> led to statues of Macdonald being vandalized and removed in other cities in the first decades of the 21st century. The Regina memorial was vandalized at least three times between 2012 and 2018.<ref name=\"Postey\">{{cite news |last1=Postey |first1=Drew |title=Despite recent controversy Mayor Fougere disappointed to see MacDonald statue vandalized |url=https://www.620ckrm.com/2018/08/22/despite-recent-controversy-mayor-fougere-dissapinted-to-see/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=620 CKRM |date=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Call for removal===\nIn August 2017, a [[petition]] was launched for the removal of the Regina memorial.<ref name=\"Petition\">{{cite news |title=Petition calls for removal of John A. Macdonald statue in Regina |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/petition-remove-john-a-macdonald-statue-regina-1.4266149 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[CBC News]] |agency=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=29 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the removal of a statue in [[Victoria, British Columbia]] in 2018, the Regina memorial was the only Macdonald statue still standing in a major city in [[Western Canada]], one of a \"handful\" across the country.<ref name=\"Latimer\">{{cite news |last1=Latimer |first1=Kendall |title=Last John A. Macdonald statue in major Western Canada city seen painted 'red handed' |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/john-a-macdonald-statue-regina-vandalism-1.4795082 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=CBC News |date=23 August 2018}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|name=first|Statues elsewhere in Canada include the [[Macdonald Monument]] in Montreal and smaller works in [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]], [[Baden, Ontario|Baden]], and Macondald's home town [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]].<ref name=\"Yun\">{{cite journal |last1=Yun |first1=Tom |title=Where Sir John A. Macdonald stands in Canada: an interactive map |journal=[[Maclean's]] |date=19 August 2018 |url=https://www.macleans.ca/news/canada/where-sir-john-a-macdonald-stands-in-canada-an-interactive-map/ |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>}} That year, it was vandalized with spray paint in February<ref>{{cite news |title=John A. MacDonald statue in Victoria Park vandalized |url=https://www.cruzfm.com/syn/343/161331/john-a-macdonald-statue-in-victoria-park-vandalized/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=Cruz FM |date=23 February 2018}}</ref> and again on 21 August.<ref name=\"Latimer\" /> [[Vibank]] musician Patrick Johnson contacted the ''[[Regina Leader-Post]]'' to claim responsibility, saying it was an act of \"peaceful protest\", and that he painted the statue's hands red \"to symbolize the blood... on Macdonald's hands.\"<ref name=\"Johnson\">{{cite web |title=John A. Macdonald statue vandal says he painted Regina monument as a 'peaceful protest' |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/john-a-macdonald-vandal-patrick-johnson-1.4801743 |website=CBC News |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> He claimed to have painted the statue once before, after the verdict in [[Gerald Stanley]]'s trial.<ref name=\"Johnson\" />\n\n===Opposition to removal===\nRegina's mayor Michael Fougere characterized calls for the statue to remove the statue as trying \"to erase history\", but said he would be  receptive to the idea of a plaque that would \"contextualize\" Macdonald, since \"many things that he did are certainly difficult to accept by today's standards \u2014 and we should know about that.\"<ref name=\"Fougere\" /> After the statue was vandalized for the third time August 2018, he reiterated his earlier statements, and added \"it's important to remember MacDonald's contributions to Indigenous and women's voting rights.\"<ref name=\"Postey\" />\n\n==Note==\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord |50.447547|N|104.612346|W|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sir John A. Macdonald Statue}}\n[[Category:1967 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Regina, Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:John A. Macdonald]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Saskatchewan]]\n", "name_user": "ZarhanFastfire", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNote", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_A._Macdonald_Memorial_(Grandmaison)"}
{"title_page": "Natalie Barr", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Natalie Barr\n| image              = Natalie Barr (17411849208).jpg\n| caption            = Natalie Barr in 2015 at the InStyle Awards\n| birth_name         = Natalie Anne Barr\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1968|03|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bunbury, Western Australia]], Australia\n| education          = [[Curtin University]]\n| residence          = [[Sydney]], New South Wales, Australia\n| employer           = [[Seven Network]]\n| occupation         = [[Journalist]], [[news presenter|news]] and [[Television presenter|TV presenter]]\n| years_active       = 1994\u2212present \n| spouse             = Andrew\n| children           = 2\n| website            = \n| awards             = \n}}\n\n'''Natalie Anne Barr''' (born 19 March 1968) is an Australian journalist, news presenter and television presenter.\n\nBarr is currently news presenter on the [[Seven Network]]'s ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]].''\n\n==Career==\nBarr attended [[Bunbury Catholic College]] as head girl in her final year and then studied [[journalism]] at [[Curtin University]]. She worked in newspaper, radio and television journalism, including stints at the Wanneroo Times and [[Golden West Network]], before moving to [[Los Angeles]] and working for [[KABC-TV|KABC]], [[KTLA]] and [[KCOP]]. While there she was awarded a ''Golden Mic'' for best newscast writing and was nominated for a Los Angeles area [[Emmy Award]] for her work on the [[O.J. Simpson]] car chase.\n\nBarr joined ''[[Seven News]]'' in Sydney as a reporter in 1994 and also presented afternoon news updates.\n\nBarr has been the [[news presenter]] on the [[Seven Network]]'s ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' since 2003, after a stint as fill-in presenter over summer proved her popularity with the audience. She has previously presented other bulletins at Seven including ''[[Seven News|Seven Morning News]]'' and ''[[Seven News|Seven Late News]]'', and ''[[Weekend Sunrise|Sunday Sunrise]]''.\n\nIn July 2008, Barr began presenting ''[[Seven News#Seven Early News|Seven Early News]]'' alongside [[Mark Beretta]] at 5.30am, which leads into ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' where she is still the news presenter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,24007098-5006002,00.html|title=Sunrise plays catch up to Today Show|date=2008-07-12|work=[[news.com.au]]|accessdate=2008-07-12}}</ref> Barr is also the regular fill in for both [[David Koch (television presenter)|David Koch]] and [[Samantha Armytage]] on ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' and occasionally fills-in on ''Seven News Sydney''.\n\nBarr was a front-runner to co-host ''[[Sunday Night (Australian TV program)|Sunday Night]]'', a new current affairs show,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,24828329-5006014,00.html|title=Sunday night suspense|last=Reines|first=Ros|date=2008-12-21|work=[[news.com.au]]|accessdate=2009-03-27}}</ref> however [[Chris Bath]] was appointed as co-host with [[Mike Munro]].\n\nNatalie made a guest appearance on ''[[Home and Away]]'' 16 April 2018, appearing as herself reporting that missing girl Ava Gilbert.\n\n==Personal life==\nBarr was born in [[Bunbury, Western Australia]] and is married to Andrew (a television commercial editor). They have two sons.<ref>[http://svc031.wic022p.server-web.com/editorial/ShowStory.asp?StoryID=399&Redir=1 VIP Mum Profile: Natalie Barr]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Natalie Barr}}\n*[https://7news.com.au/sunrise Sunrise]\n*[http://www.entertainoz.com.au/celebrities.cfm?oid=19910 EntertainOZ celebrity speakers]\n*{{IMDb name|1745555}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' <br>News Presenter |before= Originator |after=Incumbent |years=2002 - present}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[Seven News|Seven Early News]]'' <br>Presenter |before= Originator |after=[[Jodie Speers]] |years=2008 - 2016}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SevenNewsAnchors}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barr, Natalie}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Seven News presenters]]\n[[Category:Australian television journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Sydney]]\n[[Category:People from Bunbury, Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Curtin University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Natalie Barr\n| image              = Natalie Barr (17411849208).jpg\n| caption            = Natalie Barr in 2015 at the InStyle Awards\n| birth_name         = Natalie Anne Barr\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1968|03|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bunbury, Western Australia]], Australia\n| education          = [[Curtin University]]\n| residence          = [[Sydney]], New South Wales, Australia\n| employer           = [[Seven Network]]\n| occupation         = [[Journalist]], [[news presenter|news]] and [[Television presenter|TV presenter]]\n| years_active       = 1994\u2212present \n| spouse             = Andrew\n| children           = 2\n| website            = \n| awards             = \n}}\n\n'''Natalie Anne Barr''' (born 19 March 1968) is an Australian journalist, news presenter and television presenter.\n\nBarr is currently news presenter on the [[Seven Network]]'s ''[[Unrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]].''\n\n==Career==\nBarr attended [[Bunbury Catholic College]] as head girl in her final year and then studied [[journalism]] at [[Curtin University]]. She worked in newspaper, radio and television journalism, including stints at the Wanneroo Times and [[Golden West Network]], before moving to [[Los Angeles]] and working for [[KABC-TV|KABC]], [[KTLA]] and [[KCOP]]. While there she was awarded a ''Golden Mic'' for best newscast writing and was nominated for a Los Angeles area [[Emmy Award]] for her work on the [[O.J. Simpson]] car chase.\n\nBarr joined ''[[Seven News]]'' in Sydney as a reporter in 1994 and also presented afternoon news updates.\n\nBarr has been the [[news presenter]] on the [[Seven Network]]'s ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' since 2003, after a stint as fill-in presenter over summer proved her popularity with the audience. She has previously presented other bulletins at Seven including ''[[Seven News|Seven Morning News]]'' and ''[[Seven News|Seven Late News]]'', and ''[[Weekend Sunrise|Sunday Sunrise]]''.\n\nIn July 2008, Barr began presenting ''[[Seven News#Seven Early News|Seven Early News]]'' alongside [[Mark Beretta]] at 5.30am, which leads into ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' where she is still the news presenter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,24007098-5006002,00.html|title=Sunrise plays catch up to Today Show|date=2008-07-12|work=[[news.com.au]]|accessdate=2008-07-12}}</ref> Barr is also the regular fill in for both [[David Koch (television presenter)|David Koch]] and [[Samantha Armytage]] on ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' and occasionally fills-in on ''Seven News Sydney''.\n\nBarr was a front-runner to co-host ''[[Sunday Night (Australian TV program)|Sunday Night]]'', a new current affairs show,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,24828329-5006014,00.html|title=Sunday night suspense|last=Reines|first=Ros|date=2008-12-21|work=[[news.com.au]]|accessdate=2009-03-27}}</ref> however [[Chris Bath]] was appointed as co-host with [[Mike Munro]].\n\nNatalie made a guest appearance on ''[[Home and Away]]'' 16 April 2018, appearing as herself reporting that missing girl Ava Gilbert.\n\n==Personal life==\nBarr was born in [[Bunbury, Western Australia]] and is married to Andrew (a television commercial editor). They have two sons.<ref>[http://svc031.wic022p.server-web.com/editorial/ShowStory.asp?StoryID=399&Redir=1 VIP Mum Profile: Natalie Barr]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Natalie Barr}}\n*[https://7news.com.au/sunrise Sunrise]\n*[http://www.entertainoz.com.au/celebrities.cfm?oid=19910 EntertainOZ celebrity speakers]\n*{{IMDb name|1745555}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' <br>News Presenter |before= Originator |after=Incumbent |years=2002 - present}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[Seven News|Seven Early News]]'' <br>Presenter |before= Originator |after=[[Jodie Speers]] |years=2008 - 2016}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SevenNewsAnchors}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barr, Natalie}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Seven News presenters]]\n[[Category:Australian television journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Sydney]]\n[[Category:People from Bunbury, Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Curtin University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "203.214.83.238", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natalie_Barr"}
{"title_page": "Legibility", "text_new": "{{For|the series of typefaces|Legibility Group}}\n\n'''Legibility''' is the ease with which a reader can decode symbols. In addition to [[written language]], it can also refer to behaviour<ref name=\"Weisman 1981\"/> or architecture,<ref name=\"Architectural Legibility\"/> for example. From the perspective of [[communication research]], it can be described as a measure of the permeability of a [[communication channel]]. A large number of known factors can affect legibility.\n\nIn everyday language, legibility is commonly used as a synonym for [[readability]]. In [[graphic design]], however, legibility is often distinguished from readability. Readability is the ease with which a reader can follow and understand words, sentences and paragraphs. While legibility usually refers to the visual clarity of individual symbols, readability is more about their arrangement or even the choice of words.<ref name=\"Tracy 1986\"/><ref name=\"Lieberman 1967\"/>\nLegibility is a component of readability.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe legibility of text is most often examined by controlled deterioration of viewing conditions and determination of threshold detection.<ref name=\"letter superiority\"/>\n\n==Influencing factors==\nThe legibility of visual displays (e.g. text) depends on:\n*conditions such as sufficient brightness contrast between symbols and their background\n*the viewing distance (\u2013 which affects the angular size of the symbols \u2013, and to a lesser extent on the resolution<ref name=\"letter superiority\"/>)\n*the font design.<ref name=\"Smith 1979\"/>\n*vibrations (e.g. from walking), which affect the human visual system.<ref name=\"Mustonen Olkkonen Hakkinen 2004\"/>\n*the reproduction quality of the presentation medium. A few decades ago, computer monitor screens were less legible than print on paper, but this is no longer true with newer screens.<ref name=\"letter superiority\"/>\n\nThe abilities and fitness of the readers also influence their threshold legibility: it has been shown that legibility correlates inversely with the age of the readers, as older readers may be impaired by adverse factors in visual design, such as small text size.\n\n\"The legibility of a typeface is related to the characteristics inherent in its design \u2026 which relate to the ability to distinguish one letter from the other.\"{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} Aspects of type design that affect legibility include \"[[x-height]], character [[shape]]s, [[Character Stroke|stroke contrast]], the [[Font size|size]] of its [[Counter (typography)|counters]], [[serif]]s or lack thereof, and [[Font weight|weight]].\"<ref name=\"Strizver 2010\"/> Other [[typography|typographic]] factors that affect legibility include [[font]] choice, [[angular diameter|angular size]] ([[point (typography)|point]] size vs. viewing distance), [[kerning]], [[Letter case|cases]] used, [[letter-spacing|tracking]], [[line length]], [[leading]], and [[typographic alignment|justification]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nReducing the stroke width below a certain point impairs legibility. [[Italic type]] is read more slowly.\n\nAt the same point size, capital letters are easier to read in Latin script; but this is reversed if the cap height of the capitals is adjusted to the x-height of the lowercase letters (in which case the lower case letters take up more space due to their ascenders and descenders.)<ref name=\"letter superiority\"/>\n\nDespite contrary opinions, serifs have little observable influence on reading speed. At low resolution, the additional spacing between letters required for the serifs seems to improve legibility, whereas otherwise they have a slightly adverse effect.<ref name=\"Arditi Cho 2005\"/> For special groups, the picture may look different: the [[dyslexia|dyslexics]] community{{clarify|date=April 2020}} seems to be convinced that serifs are unnecessary visual clutter, which makes the text less accessible and makes the letter shapes deviate more from the simpler forms known from school.\n\n[[Eye tracking|Eye tracker]] studies support the theory that increasing complexity of shapes reduces legibility.<ref name=\"eye tracker\"/> The addition of [[Harakah|vowel marks]] in [[Arabic script]] has contradictory effects, but appears to be detrimental to legibility overall.<ref name=\"eye tracker\"/> Freestanding letters are easier to recognize than ones with adjacent elements; this is known as ''crowding effect''.<ref name=\"letter superiority\"/>\n\nCommon measures to improve legibility at lowest resolution include the use of wide apertures/large open counters, large x-height, low stroke variability, etc., while some improvements like [[ink trap]]s{{clarify|date=April 2020}} are specific to different presentation media.<ref name=\"Alpaca 2016\"/>\n\nWhile a large x-height is generally considered helpful for legibility at low resolutions, the dyslexic community holds the theory that short [[Ascender (typography)|ascenders]]/descenders tend to cause confusion. Dyslexics and learners also seem to prefer less regularity between individual letterforms, especially further differentiating features in glyphs that are often just mirrored versions of other letters, as in the group b, d, p and q, since the human brain seems to have evolved to recognize (symmetrical) three-dimensional objects regardless of their orientation in space.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bettinger.at/eufont.eu/en/problems/legibility-and-readability-issues|title=Legibility and readability issues|website=EUfont.eu|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref name=\"E\u00d6DL 2013\"/> This is the basis for some of the most devout endorsements of the otherwise much hated [[Comic Sans]] typeface.<ref name=\"Baer 2017\"/> Other important aspects seem to be the familiarity of the glyph shapes, the absence of serifs, looser spacing,<ref name=\"dyslexia spacing\"/> ...<ref>http://dyslexiahelp.umich.edu/sites/default/files/good_fonts_for_dyslexia_study.pdf</ref>\nWhile textbook versions perform better with inexperienced readers/learners, most experienced readers seem to be more comfortable with the traditional two-story print forms for [[a]] and [[g]].<ref name=\"Sassoon 1993\"/><ref name=\"Beier Larson 2010\"/>\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book|last=Beier|first=Sofie|title=Reading letters : designing for legibility|publisher=BIS|publication-place=Amsterdam|year=2012|isbn=978-90-6369-271-1|oclc=751739979}} (based on [https://researchonline.rca.ac.uk/957/1/Sofie_Beier_Typeface_Legibility_2009.pdf her doctoral thesis])\n\n==See also==\n* [[Measure (typography)]]\n* [[Optical character recognition]] (OCR)\n* [[Despeckle]]\n* [[RKM code]] for a scheme optimized for legibility\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Weisman 1981\">http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.441.4679&rep=rep1&type=pdf</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Architectural Legibility\">{{Cite journal|last=Weisman|first=Jerry|date=March 1981|title=Evaluating Architectural Legibility|journal=Environment and Behavior|volume=13|issue=2|pages=189\u2013204|doi=10.1177/0013916581132004|issn=0013-9165}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Tracy 1986\">{{Cite book|last=Tracy|first=Walter|title=Letters of credit : a view of type design|publisher=David R. Godine|publication-place=London|year=1986|isbn=|oclc=|pages=30\u201332}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Lieberman 1967\">{{Cite book|last=Lieberman|first=J. Ben|title=Types of typefaces and how to recognize them|publisher=Sterling Publishing Co.|publication-place=New York|year=1967|isbn=|oclc=|pages=85\u2013127}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"letter superiority\">{{Cite journal|last=Sheedy|first=James E.|last2=Subbaram|first2=Manoj V.|last3=Zimmerman|first3=Aaron B.|last4=Hayes|first4=John R.|date=December 2005|title=Text Legibility and the Letter Superiority Effect|journal=Human Factors: The Journal of the Human Factors and Ergonomics Society|volume=47|issue=4|pages=797\u2013815|doi=10.1518/001872005775570998|issn=0018-7208|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Aaron_Zimmerman/publication/7226134_Text_Legibility_and_the_Letter_Superiority_Effect/links/561e4b3608aecade1acb6f59.pdf}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Smith 1979\">{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=Sidney L.|date=December 1979|title=Letter Size and Legibility|journal=Human Factors: The Journal of the Human Factors and Ergonomics Society|volume=21|issue=6|pages=661\u2013670|doi=10.1177/001872087912210604|issn=0018-7208}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Mustonen Olkkonen Hakkinen 2004\">{{cite conference|last=Mustonen|first=Terhi|last2=Olkkonen|first2=Maria|last3=Hakkinen|first3=Jukka|title=Examining mobile phone text legibility while walking|publisher=ACM Press|publication-place=New York, New York, USA|year=2004|isbn=1-58113-703-6|doi=10.1145/985921.986034|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Jukka_Haekkinen/publication/221517572_Examining_mobile_phone_text_legibility_while_walking/links/0fcfd5097c0bfad3d2000000/Examining-mobile-phone-text-legibility-while-walking.pdf|page=}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Strizver 2010\">{{Cite book|title=Type Rules: The Designer's Guide to Professional Typography|edition=3rd|last=Strizver|first=Ilene|year=2010|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=New Jersey|isbn=978-0-470-54251-4|page=73}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Arditi Cho 2005\">{{Cite journal|last=Arditi|first=Aries|last2=Cho|first2=Jianna|date=2005-11-01|title=Serifs and font legibility|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0042698905003007|journal=Vision Research|volume=45|issue=23|pages=2926\u20132933|doi=10.1016/j.visres.2005.06.013|issn=0042-6989|pmc=4612630|pmid=16099015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"eye tracker\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1671473/|title=Could Good Type Design Promote Literacy In The Middle East?|last=Campbell-Dollaghan|first=Kelsey|date=2013-01-30|website=Fast Company|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Alpaca 2016\">{{Cite web|url=https://blog.prototypr.io/what-to-watch-out-for-when-working-on-typography-for-print-and-web-3d754b87a3f4|title=What to watch out for when working on typography for print and web|last=Alpaca|first=U. X.|date=2016-11-01|website=Medium|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"E\u00d6DL 2013\">{{Cite book|title=Brosch\u00fcre: Schriftarten f\u00fcr legasthene Menschen|last=|date=2013-07-19|publisher=Erster \u00d6sterreichischer Dachverband Legasthenie|language=de-DE|url=https://www.legasthenie.at/broschure-schriftarten-fur-legasthene-menschen/}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Baer 2017\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2017/03/the-reason-comic-sans-is-a-public-good.html|title=The Reason Comic Sans Is a Public Good|last=Baer|first=Drake|date=2017-03-07|website=The Cut|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Sassoon 1993\">{{cite book|last=Sassoon|first=Rosemary|title=Computers and typography|publisher=Intellect|publication-place=Oxford, England|year=1993|chapter=Through the eyes of a child: perception and type design|isbn=1-871516-23-4|oclc=27468183|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gm4QAbGKIBgC&pg=PA150|pages=150\u2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Beier Larson 2010\">{{cite journal|last=Beier|first=Sofie|last2=Larson|first2=Kevin|title=Design Improvements for Frequently Misrecognized Letters 1|journal=Information Design Journal|publisher=John Benjamins Publishing Company|volume=18|issue=2|date=2010-06-01|issn=0142-5471|doi=10.1075/idj.18.2.03bei|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/233608849|pages=118\u2013137}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"dyslexia spacing\">{{Cite journal|last=Zorzi|first=M.|last2=Barbiero|first2=C.|last3=Facoetti|first3=A.|last4=Lonciari|first4=I.|last5=Carrozzi|first5=M.|last6=Montico|first6=M.|last7=Bravar|first7=L.|last8=George|first8=F.|last9=Pech-Georgel|first9=C.|last10=Ziegler|first10=J. C.|date=2012-06-04|title=Extra-large letter spacing improves reading in dyslexia|url=https://www.pnas.org/content/109/28/11455.short|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=109|issue=28|pages=11455\u201311459|doi=10.1073/pnas.1205566109|issn=0027-8424}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|legibility}}\n* {{cite web|url= http://www.hathitrust.org/technical_reports/Legibility.pdf|title= Legibility and Large-Scale Digitization|author= Jeremy York|date= November 2008|publisher= Hathitrust Digital Library|accessdate= 12 August 2012}}\n\n[[Category:Writing]]\n[[Category:Typography]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the series of typefaces|Legibility Group}}\n\n'''Legibility''' is the ease with which a reader can decode symbols. In addition to [[written language]], it can also refer to behaviour<ref name=\"Weisman 1981\"/> or architecture,<ref name=\"Architectural Legibility\"/> for example. From the perspective of [[communication research]], it can be described as a measure of the permeability of a [[communication channel]]. A large number of known factors can affect legibility.\n\nIn everyday language, legibility is commonly used as a synonym for [[readability]]. In [[graphic design]], however, legibility is often distinguished from readability. Readability is the ease with which a reader can follow and understand words, sentences and paragraphs. While legibility usually refers to the visual clarity of individual symbols, readability is more about their arrangement or even the choice of words.<ref name=\"Tracy 1986\"/><ref name=\"Lieberman 1967\"/>\nLegibility is a component of readability.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe legibility of text is most often examined by controlled deterioration of viewing conditions and determination of threshold detection.<ref name=\"letter superiority\"/>\n\n==Influencing factors==\nThe legibility of visual displays (e.g. text) depends on:\n*conditions such as sufficient brightness contrast between symbols and their background\n*the viewing distance (\u2013 which affects the angular size of the symbols \u2013, and to a lesser extent on the resolution<ref name=\"letter superiority\"/>)\n*the font design.<ref name=\"Smith 1979\"/>\n*vibrations (e.g. from walking), which affect the human visual system.<ref name=\"Mustonen Olkkonen Hakkinen 2004\"/>\n*the reproduction quality of the presentation medium. A few decades ago, computer monitor screens were less legible than print on paper, but this is no longer true with newer screens.<ref name=\"letter superiority\"/>\n\nThe abilities and fitness of the readers also influence their threshold legibility: it has been shown that legibility correlates inversely with the age of the readers, as older readers may be impaired by adverse factors in visual design, such as small text size.\n\n\"The legibility of a typeface is related to the characteristics inherent in its design \u2026 which relate to the ability to distinguish one letter from the other.\"{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} Aspects of type design that affect legibility include \"[[x-height]], character [[shape]]s, [[Character Stroke|stroke contrast]], the [[Font size|size]] of its [[Counter (typography)|counters]], [[serif]]s or lack thereof, and [[Font weight|weight]].\"<ref name=\"Strizver 2010\"/> Other [[typography|typographic]] factors that affect legibility include [[font]] choice, [[angular diameter|angular size]] ([[point (typography)|point]] size vs. viewing distance), [[kerning]], [[Letter case|cases]] used, [[letter-spacing|tracking]], [[line length]], [[leading]], and [[typographic alignment|justification]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nReducing the stroke width below a certain point impairs legibility. [[Italic type]] is read more slowly.\n\nAt the same point size, capital letters are easier to read in Latin script; but this is reversed if the cap height of the capitals is adjusted to the x-height of the lowercase letters (in which case the lower case letters take up more space due to their ascenders and descenders.)<ref name=\"letter superiority\"/>\n\nDespite contrary opinions, serifs have little observable influence on reading speed. At low resolution, the additional spacing between letters required for the serifs seems to improve legibility, whereas otherwise they have a slightly adverse effect.<ref name=\"Arditi Cho 2005\"/> For special groups, the picture may look different: the [[dyslexia|dyslexics]] community{{clarify|date=April 2020}} seems to be convinced that serifs are unnecessary visual clutter, which makes the text less accessible and makes the letter shapes deviate more from the simpler forms known from school.\n\n[[Eye tracking|Eye tracker]] studies support the theory that increasing complexity of shapes reduces legibility.<ref name=\"eye tracker\"/> The addition of [[Harakah|vowel marks]] in [[Arabic script]] has contradictory effects, but appears to be detrimental to legibility overall.<ref name=\"eye tracker\"/> Freestanding letters are easier to recognize than ones with adjacent elements; this is known as ''crowding effect''.<ref name=\"letter superiority\"/>\n\nCommon measures to improve legibility at lowest resolution include the use of wide apertures/large open counters, large x-height, low stroke variability, etc., while some improvements like [[ink traps]]{{clarify|date=April 2020}} are specific to different presentation media.<ref name=\"Alpaca 2016\"/>\n\nWhile a large x-height is generally considered helpful for legibility at low resolutions, the dyslexic community holds the theory that short [[Ascender (typography)|ascenders]]/descenders tend to cause confusion. Dyslexics and learners also seem to prefer less regularity between individual letterforms, especially further differentiating features in glyphs that are often just mirrored versions of other letters, as in the group b, d, p and q, since the human brain seems to have evolved to recognize (symmetrical) three-dimensional objects regardless of their orientation in space.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bettinger.at/eufont.eu/en/problems/legibility-and-readability-issues|title=Legibility and readability issues|website=EUfont.eu|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref name=\"E\u00d6DL 2013\"/> This is the basis for some of the most devout endorsements of the otherwise much hated [[Comic Sans]] typeface.<ref name=\"Baer 2017\"/> Other important aspects seem to be the familiarity of the glyph shapes, the absence of serifs, looser spacing,<ref name=\"dyslexia spacing\"/> ...<ref>http://dyslexiahelp.umich.edu/sites/default/files/good_fonts_for_dyslexia_study.pdf</ref>\nWhile textbook versions perform better with inexperienced readers/learners, most experienced readers seem to be more comfortable with the traditional two-story print forms for [[a]] and [[g]].<ref name=\"Sassoon 1993\"/><ref name=\"Beier Larson 2010\"/>\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book|last=Beier|first=Sofie|title=Reading letters : designing for legibility|publisher=BIS|publication-place=Amsterdam|year=2012|isbn=978-90-6369-271-1|oclc=751739979}} (based on [https://researchonline.rca.ac.uk/957/1/Sofie_Beier_Typeface_Legibility_2009.pdf her doctoral thesis])\n\n==See also==\n* [[Measure (typography)]]\n* [[Optical character recognition]] (OCR)\n* [[Despeckle]]\n* [[RKM code]] for a scheme optimized for legibility\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Weisman 1981\">http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.441.4679&rep=rep1&type=pdf</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Architectural Legibility\">{{Cite journal|last=Weisman|first=Jerry|date=March 1981|title=Evaluating Architectural Legibility|journal=Environment and Behavior|volume=13|issue=2|pages=189\u2013204|doi=10.1177/0013916581132004|issn=0013-9165}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Tracy 1986\">{{Cite book|last=Tracy|first=Walter|title=Letters of credit : a view of type design|publisher=David R. Godine|publication-place=London|year=1986|isbn=|oclc=|pages=30\u201332}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Lieberman 1967\">{{Cite book|last=Lieberman|first=J. Ben|title=Types of typefaces and how to recognize them|publisher=Sterling Pub