Liga]]||30||19||7||4||46||20||64||bgcolor=silver|2nd||[[2014\u201315 Serbian Cup|R2]]|| ||align=left|{{flagicon|SRB}} [[Darko Lazovi\u0107]]||10||\n|-\n![[2015\u201316 Red Star Belgrade season|2015\u201316]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Serbian SuperLiga|Serbian SuperLiga]]||37||30||5||2||97||27||54||bgcolor=gold|1st||[[2015\u201316 Serbian Cup|R2]]||[[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] \u2013 [[2015\u201316 UEFA Europa League|QR1]] ||align=left|{{flagicon|SRB}} [[Aleksandar Katai]]||23||\n|-\n!rowspan=2|2016\u201317\n|rowspan=2|[[2016\u201317 Serbian SuperLiga|Serbian SuperLiga]]||rowspan=2|37||rowspan=2|30||rowspan=2|4||rowspan=2|3||rowspan=2|93||rowspan=2|33||rowspan=2|55||bgcolor=silver rowspan=2|2nd||bgcolor=silver rowspan=2|[[2016\u201317 Serbian Cup|Runners-up]]||[[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] \u2013 [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League|QR3]] ||align=left rowspan=2|{{flagicon|GHA}} [[Richmond Boakye]]||rowspan=2|16||rowspan=2|\n|-\n|[[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] \u2013 [[2016\u201317 UEFA Europa League|Play off]]\n|-\n![[2017\u201318 Red Star Belgrade season|2017\u201318]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Serbian SuperLiga|Serbian SuperLiga]]||37||32||4||1||96||19||60||bgcolor=gold|1st||[[2017\u201318 Serbian Cup|QF]]||[[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] \u2013 [[2017\u201318 UEFA Europa League#Round of 32|Round of 32]]||align=left|{{flagicon|SRB}} [[Aleksandar Pe\u0161i\u0107]] ||29||{{ref|p|16}}\n|-\n![[2018\u201319 Red Star Belgrade season|2018\u201319]]\n|[[2018\u201319 Serbian SuperLiga|Serbian SuperLiga]]||37||33||3||1||94||20||60||bgcolor=gold|1st||bgcolor=silver|[[2018\u201319 Serbian Cup|Runners-up]]||[[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] \u2013 [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League#Group Stage|Group Stage]]||align=left|{{flagicon|COM}} [[El Fardou Ben Nabouhane|Ben]] ||25 ||{{ref|q|17}}\n|-\n![[2019\u201320 Red Star Belgrade season|2019\u201320]]\n|[[2019\u201320 Serbian SuperLiga|Serbian SuperLiga]]|| || || || || || || || || ||[[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] \u2013 [[2019\u201320 UEFA Champions League#Group Stage|Group Stage]]||align=left| || ||\n|}\n\n:1{{note|a}} Goals in all competitions are counted.\n:2{{note|b}} First title in domestic cup competitions.\n:3{{note|c}} First title in domestic league competitions.\n:4{{note|d}} The 1952 season was shortened and sped-up. The reason for the changes was a desire to implement the fall-spring competition format. Competition took place in two phases. In first clubs were divided into two preliminary groups of 6 teams each. Based on their ranking at the end of preliminary groups they were promoted to three groups: Title, Central and Relegation. Each of them containing 4 teams. \n:5{{note|e}} Cup competition was not held for 1955\u201356 and 1974\u201375 seasons.\n:6{{note|f}} First season in which club entered European competitions.\n:7{{note|g}} First final in European competitions.\n:8{{note|h}} Between 1988-89 and 1991-92, drawn games went to penalties with the winners of the shoot out gaining the point. Figures in brackets represent points won in such shoot outs.\n:9{{note|i}} First European title.\n:10{{note|j}} First season of [[Federal Republic of Yugoslavia]]'s League.\n:11{{note|k}} Was unable to compete in European competitions due to UN sanctions. \n:12{{note|l}} Between 1993-94 and 1995-96 league was divided into 2 groups, A and B, of 10 teams each. In the first half of competition teams played each other twice, and based on number of points won and their position, each team was given certain amount of \"bonus points\". In the start of spring part of competition 4 last teams from A league were drop to B league, and replaced by top 4 teams from B league. Again teams played each others twice, and in the end final positions were determined by sum of points won at the end of Spring part of competition and bonus points won in the Fall part of competition. \n:13{{note|m}} From this season onward for victory was awarded 3 points instead of 2.\n:14{{note|n}} First season of [[Serbia and Montenegro]]'s League.\n:15{{note|o}} First season of [[Serbian SuperLiga]].\n:16{{note|p}} Managed to qualify for group stage and advance through it for the first time since [[UEFA Europa League]] was established in 2009.\n:17{{note|q}} Managed to qualify for group stage for the first time since [[UEFA Champions League]] was established in 1992.\n\n{{Red Star Belgrade}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Red Star Belgrade Seasons}}\n[[Category:Red Star Belgrade seasons| ]]\n[[Category:Serbian football club seasons]]\n[[Category:Belgrade-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "SotirSoca", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Red_Star_Belgrade_seasons"}
{"title_page": "Elections in Nigeria", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Politics of Nigeria}}\n'''Elections in Nigeria''' are forms of choosing representatives to the Nigerian federal government and the various states in the [[Fourth Nigerian Republic|fourth republic]] [[politics of Nigeria|Nigeria]].\n\n==Background==\nNigerians elects on the federal level a [[head of state]] (the [[President of Nigeria]])  and a [[legislature]] (the [[Nigerian National Assembly|National Assembly]]). The president is elected by the people. The National Assembly has two [[bicameralism|chambers]]. The '[[Nigerian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] has 360 members, elected for a four-year term in single-seat [[constituency|constituencies]]. The [[Nigerian Senate|Senate]] has 109 members, elected for a four-year term: each of the [[States of Nigeria|36 states]] are divided into 3 senatorial districts, each of which is represented by one senator; the [[Federal Capital Territory, Nigeria|Federal Capital Territory]] is represented by only one senator.\n\nNigeria has a [[multi-party]] system, with two or three strong [[political parties|parties]] and a third party that is electorally successful. However, members of the [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|People's Democratic Party]] (PDP) had controlled the presidency since elections were resumed in 1999 until 2015 when Muhammadu Buhari won the presidential election.\n\n==2007 elections==\n{{Main|2007 Nigerian general election}}\nThe Nigerian general elections of 2007 were held on 14 April and 21 April 2007.<ref name=\"MG-elections\">Ola Awoniyi: [http://www.mg.co.za/articlepage.aspx?area=/breaking_news/breaking_news__africa/&articleid=282393 \"Nigeria sets date for elections\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913010829/http://mg.co.za/articlepage.aspx?area=%2Fbreaking_news%2Fbreaking_news__africa%2F&articleid=282393 |date=13 September 2012 }}, ''Mail & Guardian''. 29 August 2006.</ref> Governorship and state assembly elections were held on 14 April, while the presidential and national assembly elections were held a week later on 21 April. [[Umaru Yar'Adua]] won the highly controversial election for the ruling [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|People's Democratic Party]] (PDP) and was sworn in on 29 May.\n\nThe ruling PDP won 26 of the 32 states, according to INEC, including [[Kaduna State]] and [[Katsina State]], where the results were contested by the local population.<ref>Barry Moody, [http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L16160690.htm \"Nigeria court clears way for late presidential bid\"], Reuters (Alertnet.org), 16  April 2007.</ref>\n\nFollowing the presidential election, groups monitoring the election gave it a dismal assessment.\nChief [[European Union]] observer Max van den Berg reported that the handling of the polls had \"fallen far short\" of basic international standards, and that \"the process cannot be considered to be credible.\"<ref name=\"SMH24April\">[http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/nigeria-election-worst-ever-seen/2007/04/24/1177180600209.html \"Nigeria election 'worst ever seen'\"], SMH News, 24 April 2007.</ref>  A spokesman for the [[United States Department of State]] said it was \"deeply troubled\" by election polls, calling them \"flawed\", and said it hoped the political parties would resolve any differences over the election through peaceful, constitutional means.<ref name=Huge>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6584393.stm \"Huge win for Nigeria's Yar'Adua\"], BBC News, 23 April 2007.</ref>\n\n==2011 elections==\n{{Main|2011 Nigerian presidential election|Nigerian parliamentary election, 2011}}\n{{Update|section|date=November 2013}}\n\nA parliamentary election was held in [[Nigeria]] on 9 April 2011. The election was originally scheduled to be held on 2 April,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allwestafrica.com/240920106989.html |title=Nigeria\u2019s General Elections Postponed From January To April As A New Voter Registration Software Is Released By The Inec - West African News |publisher=Allwestafrica.com |date=2010-09-24 |accessdate=2011-04-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101202230837/http://www.allwestafrica.com/240920106989.html |archive-date=2 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-11825092 |title= Nigeria to hold presidential election on 9 April |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2010-11-23 |accessdate=2011-04-19}}</ref> but was later postponed to 4 April.<ref>{{cite web|author=the CNN Wire Staff |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/04/02/nigeria.election/ |title=Nigeria postpones parliamentary election - CNN.com |publisher=Edition.cnn.com |date= |accessdate=2011-04-09}}</ref>\n\nA presidential election was held in [[Nigeria]] on 16 April 2011, postponed from 9 April 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-11825092 | work=BBC News | title=Nigeria to hold presidential election on 9 April | date=23 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"allwest\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.allwestafrica.com/240920106989.html |title=Nigeria\u2019s General Elections Postponed From January To April As A New Voter Registration Software Is Released By The Inec - All West Africa News<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=6 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101202230837/http://www.allwestafrica.com/240920106989.html |archive-date=2 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2011/04/201143174718212830.html | work=Aljazeera News | title=Nigeria Elections postponed for second time | date=3 April 2011}}</ref> The election follows controversy as to whether a [[Islam in Nigeria|Muslim]] or [[Christianity in Nigeria|Christian]] should be allowed to become president given the tradition of rotating the top office between the religions and following the death of [[Umaru Yar'Adua]], who was a Muslim, and [[Goodluck Jonathan]], a Christian, assuming the interim presidency.\n\nFollowing the election widespread violence took place in the northern parts of the country.<ref>{{Cite news \n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = Jonathan rival rejects vote result as thousands flee Nigeria unrest \n  | newspaper = Daily Nation\n  | location = Kenya\n  | pages = \n  | language = \n  | publisher = \n  | date = 20 April 2011\n  | url = http://www.nation.co.ke/News/africa/-/1066/1148266/-/12k89km/-/index.html\n  | accessdate = 21 April 2011}}</ref> Goodluck Jonathan was declared the winner on 19 April.<ref name=cnn>{{cite news|last=Purefoy|first=Christian|title=Widespread election violence erupts in Nigeria|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/04/19/nigeria.election/?hpt=T1|publisher=CNN|accessdate=20 April 2011|date=19 April 2011}}</ref> The elections was reported in the international media as having run smoothly with relatively little violence or voter fraud in contrast to previous elections, in particular the widely disputed 2007 election.<ref name=\"New York\">{{cite news|last=Nossiter|first=Adam|title=Nigerians Vote in Presidential Election|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/17/world/africa/17nigeria.html?pagewanted=1&_r=1&hp|accessdate=17 April 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=16 April 2011}}</ref> The [[United States]] [[State Department]] said the election was \"successful\" and a \"substantial improvement\" over 2007, although it added that vote rigging and fraud also took place.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Recent Elections in Nigeria|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/p/af/rls/spbr/2011/161931.htm}}</ref>\n\n==2015 elections==\n{{main|2015 Nigerian general election}}\nThe 2015 general elections was originally scheduled to hold 14 February, but was later postponed to 28 March{Presidential, Senatorial and House of Representatives} and 11 April 2015 {Governorship and state house of Assembly}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inecnigeria.org/|title=INEC Nigeria|website=www.inecnigeria.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-20}}</ref>  General Muhammadu Buhari of the [[All Progressives Congress]] emerged as the winner of the Presidential elections and was sworn in on 29 May 2015. It was the first time in the history of [[Nigeria]] that an incumbent President lost an election. [[Goodluck Jonathan|Goodluck Ebele Johnathan]] of the [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|People's Democratic Party]] lost his seat to [[Muhammadu Buhari]] of the [[All Progressives Congress]] .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.oauife.edu.ng/todeyemi/publications/stakeholders-information-and-communication-technologies-platforms-and-2015-gen|title=Stakeholders, Information and Communication Technologies platforms and the 2015 General Elections in Nigeria|last=Odeyemi|date=2015|access-date=2018-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==2019 elections==\n{{main|2019 Nigerian general election}}\nPresidential and  National Assembly Elections were scheduled for 16 February 2019, while State and Local government elections were scheduled for 2 March 2019. Elections were postponed by one week after INEC cited logistic challenges <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/313199-its-official-inec-postpones-all-nigerias-general-elections.html |title=It\u2019s Official: INEC postpones all Nigeria\u2019s general elections |website=Premium Times |language=en |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n. The rescheduled dates are 23 February and 9 March 2019.\n\nPresident [[Muhammadu Buhari]] was re-elected for another four-year term. The primary contender was former vice president, Atiku Abubakar of the [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|People's Democratic Party]] (PDP).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legit.ng/tag/elections-2019-nigeria.html|title=Presidential Elections 2019 in Nigeria|website=Legit.ng - Nigeria news.|language=en|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref>\n[[Kingsley Moghalu]] of the Young Progressives Party (YPP), Yele Sowore of the African Action Congress (AAC) and [[Fela Durotoye]] of the Alliance for a New Nigeria (ANN) were other popular candidates who are all relatively young. Late last year these three parties alongside some others attempted to form a coalition.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Toromade |first1=Samson |title=How PACT crumbled before and after Fela Durotoye beat Moghalu to emerge consensus candidate |url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/politics/2019-elections-how-pact-crumbled-before-and-after-fela-durotoye-beat-moghalu-to/72mxrzq |website=www.pulse.ng |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> However, the candidates pulled out of the coalition and decided to continue running on their respective platforms. There are 73 candidates contesting in the presidential election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.guardian.ng/politics/73-candidates-for-presidential-election-says-inec/ |title=73 candidates for presidential election, says INEC |website=Guardian Newspapers |language=en |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n\nThe 2019 governorship and state house of assembly election was earlier scheduled for 2 March 2019 was rescheduled for Saturday 9, March 2019. With two major political parties; [[All Progressives Congress]] (APC) and [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|People's Democratic Party]] fielding candidates in the elections across various states except Rivers where a court order prohibits The [[All Progressives Congress]] from fielding candidates as a result of internal crisis with the state chapter of the party.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Electoral calendar]]\n* [[Electoral system]]\n* [[Open ballot system]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://africanelections.tripod.com/ng.html African Elections Database]\n*[http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/n/nigeria/ Adam Carr's Election Archive]\n\n{{Nigerian elections}}\n{{Africa in topic|Elections in}}\n{{Nigeria topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elections In Nigeria}}\n[[Category:Elections in Nigeria| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Politics of Nigeria}}\n'''Elections in Nigeria''' are forms of choosing representatives to the Nigerian federal government and the various states in the [[Fourth Nigerian Republic|fourth republic]] [[politics of Nigeria|Nigeria]].\n\n==Background==\nNigerians elects on the federal level a [[head of state]] (the [[President of Nigeria]])  and a [[legislature]] (the [[Nigerian National Assembly|National Assembly]]). The president is elected by the people. The National Assembly has two [[bicameralism|chambers]]. The '''[[Nigerian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]]''' has 360 members, elected for a four-year term in single-seat [[constituency|constituencies]]. The '''[[Nigerian Senate|Senate]]''' has 109 members, elected for a four-year term: each of the [[States of Nigeria|36 states]] are divided into 3 senatorial districts, each of which is represented by one senator; the [[Federal Capital Territory, Nigeria|Federal Capital Territory]] is represented by only one senator.\n\nNigeria has a [[multi-party]] system, with two or three strong [[political parties|parties]] and a third party that is electorally successful. However, members of the [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|People's Democratic Party]] (PDP) had controlled the presidency since elections were resumed in 1999 until 2015 when Muhammadu Buhari won the presidential election.\n\n==2007 elections==\n{{Main|2007 Nigerian general election}}\nThe '''Nigerian general elections of 2007''' were held on 14 April and 21 April 2007.<ref name=\"MG-elections\">Ola Awoniyi: [http://www.mg.co.za/articlepage.aspx?area=/breaking_news/breaking_news__africa/&articleid=282393 \"Nigeria sets date for elections\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913010829/http://mg.co.za/articlepage.aspx?area=%2Fbreaking_news%2Fbreaking_news__africa%2F&articleid=282393 |date=13 September 2012 }}, ''Mail & Guardian''. 29 August 2006.</ref> Governorship and state assembly elections were held on 14 April, while the presidential and national assembly elections were held a week later on 21 April. [[Umaru Yar'Adua]] won the highly controversial election for the ruling [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|People's Democratic Party]] (PDP) and was sworn in on 29 May.\n\nThe ruling PDP won 26 of the 32 states, according to INEC, including [[Kaduna State]] and [[Katsina State]], where the results were contested by the local population.<ref>Barry Moody, [http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L16160690.htm \"Nigeria court clears way for late presidential bid\"], Reuters (Alertnet.org), 16  April 2007.</ref>\n\nFollowing the presidential election, groups monitoring the election gave it a dismal assessment.\nChief [[European Union]] observer Max van den Berg reported that the handling of the polls had \"fallen far short\" of basic international standards, and that \"the process cannot be considered to be credible.\"<ref name=\"SMH24April\">[http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/nigeria-election-worst-ever-seen/2007/04/24/1177180600209.html \"Nigeria election 'worst ever seen'\"], SMH News, 24 April 2007.</ref>  A spokesman for the [[United States Department of State]] said it was \"deeply troubled\" by election polls, calling them \"flawed\", and said it hoped the political parties would resolve any differences over the election through peaceful, constitutional means.<ref name=Huge>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6584393.stm \"Huge win for Nigeria's Yar'Adua\"], BBC News, 23 April 2007.</ref>\n\n==2011 elections==\n{{Main|2011 Nigerian presidential election|Nigerian parliamentary election, 2011}}\n{{Update|section|date=November 2013}}\n\nA '''parliamentary election''' was held in [[Nigeria]] on 9 April 2011. The election was originally scheduled to be held on 2 April,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allwestafrica.com/240920106989.html |title=Nigeria\u2019s General Elections Postponed From January To April As A New Voter Registration Software Is Released By The Inec - West African News |publisher=Allwestafrica.com |date=2010-09-24 |accessdate=2011-04-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101202230837/http://www.allwestafrica.com/240920106989.html |archive-date=2 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-11825092 |title= Nigeria to hold presidential election on 9 April |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2010-11-23 |accessdate=2011-04-19}}</ref> but was later postponed to 4 April.<ref>{{cite web|author=the CNN Wire Staff |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/04/02/nigeria.election/ |title=Nigeria postpones parliamentary election - CNN.com |publisher=Edition.cnn.com |date= |accessdate=2011-04-09}}</ref>\n\nA '''presidential election''' was held in [[Nigeria]] on 16 April 2011, postponed from 9 April 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-11825092 | work=BBC News | title=Nigeria to hold presidential election on 9 April | date=23 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"allwest\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.allwestafrica.com/240920106989.html |title=Nigeria\u2019s General Elections Postponed From January To April As A New Voter Registration Software Is Released By The Inec - All West Africa News<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=6 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101202230837/http://www.allwestafrica.com/240920106989.html |archive-date=2 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2011/04/201143174718212830.html | work=Aljazeera News | title=Nigeria Elections postponed for second time | date=3 April 2011}}</ref> The election follows controversy as to whether a [[Islam in Nigeria|Muslim]] or [[Christianity in Nigeria|Christian]] should be allowed to become president given the tradition of rotating the top office between the religions and following the death of [[Umaru Yar'Adua]], who was a Muslim, and [[Goodluck Jonathan]], a Christian, assuming the interim presidency.\n\nFollowing the election widespread violence took place in the northern parts of the country.<ref>{{Cite news \n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = Jonathan rival rejects vote result as thousands flee Nigeria unrest \n  | newspaper = Daily Nation\n  | location = Kenya\n  | pages = \n  | language = \n  | publisher = \n  | date = 20 April 2011\n  | url = http://www.nation.co.ke/News/africa/-/1066/1148266/-/12k89km/-/index.html\n  | accessdate = 21 April 2011}}</ref> Goodluck Jonathan was declared the winner on 19 April.<ref name=cnn>{{cite news|last=Purefoy|first=Christian|title=Widespread election violence erupts in Nigeria|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/04/19/nigeria.election/?hpt=T1|publisher=CNN|accessdate=20 April 2011|date=19 April 2011}}</ref> The elections was reported in the international media as having run smoothly with relatively little violence or voter fraud in contrast to previous elections, in particular the widely disputed 2007 election.<ref name=\"New York\">{{cite news|last=Nossiter|first=Adam|title=Nigerians Vote in Presidential Election|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/17/world/africa/17nigeria.html?pagewanted=1&_r=1&hp|accessdate=17 April 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=16 April 2011}}</ref> The [[United States]] [[State Department]] said the election was \"successful\" and a \"substantial improvement\" over 2007, although it added that vote rigging and fraud also took place.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Recent Elections in Nigeria|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/p/af/rls/spbr/2011/161931.htm}}</ref>\n\n==2015 elections==\n{{main|2015 Nigerian general election}}\nThe 2015 general elections was originally scheduled to hold 14 February, but was later postponed to 28 March{Presidential, Senatorial and House of Representatives} and 11 April 2015 {Governorship and state house of Assembly}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inecnigeria.org/|title=INEC Nigeria|website=www.inecnigeria.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-20}}</ref>  General Muhammadu Buhari of the [[All Progressives Congress]] emerged as the winner of the Presidential elections and was sworn in on 29 May 2015. It was the first time in the history of [[Nigeria]] that an incumbent President lost an election. [[Goodluck Jonathan|Goodluck Ebele Johnathan]] of the [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|People's Democratic Party]] lost his seat to [[Muhammadu Buhari]] of the [[All Progressives Congress]] .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.oauife.edu.ng/todeyemi/publications/stakeholders-information-and-communication-technologies-platforms-and-2015-gen|title=Stakeholders, Information and Communication Technologies platforms and the 2015 General Elections in Nigeria|last=Odeyemi|date=2015|access-date=2018-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==2019 elections==\n{{main|2019 Nigerian general election}}\nPresidential and  National Assembly Elections were scheduled for 16 February 2019, while State and Local government elections were scheduled for 2 March 2019. Elections were postponed by one week after INEC cited logistic challenges <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/313199-its-official-inec-postpones-all-nigerias-general-elections.html |title=It\u2019s Official: INEC postpones all Nigeria\u2019s general elections |website=Premium Times |language=en |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n. The rescheduled dates are 23 February and 9 March 2019.\n\nPresident [[Muhammadu Buhari]] was re-elected for another four-year term. The primary contender was former vice president, Atiku Abubakar of the [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|People's Democratic Party]](PDP).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legit.ng/tag/elections-2019-nigeria.html|title=Presidential Elections 2019 in Nigeria|website=Legit.ng - Nigeria news.|language=en|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref>\n[[Kingsley Moghalu]] of the Young Progressives Party (YPP), Yele Sowore of the African Action Congress (AAC) and [[Fela Durotoye]] of the Alliance for a New Nigeria (ANN) were other popular candidates who are all relatively young. Late last year these three parties alongside some others attempted to form a coalition.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Toromade |first1=Samson |title=How PACT crumbled before and after Fela Durotoye beat Moghalu to emerge consensus candidate |url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/politics/2019-elections-how-pact-crumbled-before-and-after-fela-durotoye-beat-moghalu-to/72mxrzq |website=www.pulse.ng |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> However, the candidates pulled out of the coalition and decided to continue running on their respective platforms. There are 73 candidates contesting in the presidential election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.guardian.ng/politics/73-candidates-for-presidential-election-says-inec/ |title=73 candidates for presidential election, says INEC |website=Guardian Newspapers |language=en |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n\nThe 2019 governorship and state house of assembly election was earlier scheduled for 2 March 2019 was rescheduled for Saturday 9, March 2019. With two major political parties; [[All Progressives Congress]](APC) and [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|People's Democratic Party]] fielding candidates in the elections across various states except Rivers where a court order prohibits The [[All Progressives Congress]] from fielding candidates as a result of internal crisis with the state chapter of the party.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Electoral calendar]]\n* [[Electoral system]]\n* [[Open ballot system]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://africanelections.tripod.com/ng.html African Elections Database]\n*[http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/n/nigeria/ Adam Carr's Election Archive]\n\n{{Nigerian elections}}\n{{Africa in topic|Elections in}}\n{{Nigeria topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elections In Nigeria}}\n[[Category:Elections in Nigeria| ]]\n", "name_user": "Ira Leviton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typos found withWikipedia:Typo_Team/mossand deleted bolds.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elections_in_Nigeria"}
